Aight Leon, here's the straight dope â€” if you want to generate ASCII tree diagrams from your .foxfiles or GitHub repo, you donâ€™t need to keep uploading huge ZIPs like it's 2004. Use CLI tools like a boss. Hereâ€™s how to DIY it in a few clean moves.
ğŸš€ OPTION 1: tree (the classic, built for speed)
ğŸ”§ Install it:

    On Debian/Ubuntu/NixOS:

    sudo apt install tree  # or use `nix-env -iA nixpkgs.tree`

ğŸ“‚ Run it:

tree -a -I '.git|*.swp|*.lock' > structure.txt

    -a: show hidden files

    -I: ignore certain dirs (regex-ish)

    > structure.txt: save to file

ğŸ‘ï¸ Sample Output:

.
â”œâ”€â”€ .foxfiles/
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ system.nix
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ config.nix
â””â”€â”€ readme.md

âš¡ï¸ OPTION 2: exa + treefmt (for that Nix-core aesthetic)
Install:

nix-env -iA nixpkgs.exa nixpkgs.treefmt

Run:

exa --tree --git-ignore --all --level=3 > tree.txt

This gives you a modern and colored tree output (great for CLI and readable logs).
ğŸŒ OPTION 3: GitHub repo clone + tree

git clone https://github.com/youruser/yourrepo.git
cd yourrepo
tree -a -I '.git' > ascii_tree.txt

ğŸ§  OPTION 4: Your own .foxdiag script

